KILL(1)                          User Commands                         KILL(1)

NAME
       kill - send a signal to a process

SYNOPSIS
       kill [-s sigspec | -sigspec] pid ...
       kill -l [sigspec]
       kill -L

DESCRIPTION
       Send  the  specified  signal to the specified processes.  The
       default signal is SIGTERM (15).

OPTIONS
       -s sigspec
              specify the signal to send by name or number

       -sigspec
              signal shorthand (e.g., -9, -HUP, -SIGTERM)

       -l [sigspec]
              list signal names.  If sigspec is a signal number, print
              the name.  If sigspec is a name, print the number.  With
              no argument, list all standard signal names.

       -L     list signal names in a table format

       -q value
              queue signal (accepted for compatibility but not
              implemented)

SIGNALS
       The following signals are recognized (with or without SIG prefix):

       HUP (1), INT (2), QUIT (3), ILL (4), TRAP (5), ABRT (6), BUS (7),
       FPE (8), KILL (9), USR1 (10), SEGV (11), USR2 (12), PIPE (13),
       ALRM (14), TERM (15), STKFLT (16), CHLD (17), CONT (18),
       STOP (19), TSTP (20), TTIN (21), TTOU (22), URG (23), XCPU (24),
       XFSZ (25), VTALRM (26), PROF (27), WINCH (28), IO (29), PWR (30),
       SYS (31)

       Real-time signals RTMIN through RTMAX are also supported, with
       RTMIN+n and RTMAX-n notation.

NOTES
       Signal numbers above 128 are treated as exit-status encodings:
       the actual signal number is computed as num - 128.

EXIT STATUS
       0      if OK

       1      if an error occurred

